# Memory-first execution

## The one choice behind Spark's speed

- Keep **intermediate results in executor RAM** between steps — don't round-trip to disk
- **Hadoop MapReduce** wrote every stage's output to disk and re-read it; that I/O dominated multi-step jobs
- Spark hands data straight to the next step; it **spills to disk only under memory pressure**

## What rides on top

- Caching, broadcast joins, adaptive query execution — all **optimizations on the memory-first core**
- Trade-off: memory is finite — oversized partitions spill, or fail with out-of-memory (→ tuning later)
